Philadelphia University of Pennsylvania Rare Book & Manuscript Library Ms. Codex 1223 4350977 http://hdl.library.upenn.edu/1017/d/medren/4350977 Bifolium with fragments from Book 37 of the Digests of Justinian I (Byzantine emperor, 527-565), containing (in order) sections of Title 7 on dowries, Title 9 on inheritance, and Title 8 on the children of marriages in which one partner is an emancipated slave. The text is surrounded by 15th-century commentary on the laws. Latin Fragments of the Digests of Justinian, Book 37, Titles 7-9 Justinian I, Emperor of the East, 483?-565 former owner Baugh, Albert C. 1891-1981 1r De dotis collatione (37.7.1.4), f. 1r 1v De ventre in possessionem mittendo et curatore eius (37.9.1), f. 1v 2r De coniungendis cum emancipato liberis eius (37.8.1.10), f. 2r

paper

 2 leaves : 429 x 289 (237 x 135) mm. bound to 439 x 295 mm Main text written in 2 columns of 50-52 lines; commentary text written in 2 columns of 90-109 lines; horizontal and vertical bounding lines ruled in lead. Written in a Gothic script. Initials (1-line to 3-line) alternating in red and blue ink, paragraph marks in red and blue ink, six-line Title 8 initial in red and blue ink. Puzzle initial, Initial S, f. 1v

Modern boards.

Probably written in France in the 15th century (Zacour-Hirsch).

Music: Contains Hufnagelschrift notation on 5-line staves in the Office of the Dead (f. 97r-107v), with later additions in square notation on 4-line staves (f. 108r-108v). Philadelphia University of Pennsylvania Rare Book & Manuscript Library Ms. Codex 1589 4936653 http://hdl.library.upenn.edu/1017/d/medren/4936653 Benedictine manuscript containing texts for Matins and Lauds from the Commemorative Office of the Virgin. This version of the Office was said most often on Saturday in place of the usual Office of the day. Also contains the Office of the Dead accompanied by musical notation for the chants. The manuscript once had leather finding tabs flush to the edge of the leaves, all but one (f. 96) of which have been torn out (for example, f. 1, 7, 69). Written in the Benedictine abbey in Elchingen (Bavaria), in 1596 (f. 96r).

1596 Elchingen Held in the abbey library no later than 1802, when the monastery was secularized and the contents of its library sent to Munich. Sold by Les Enluminures (Paris and Chicago), 2011. Translated as "An illustrated guide to Western ships." Caption title from first preface. Roll has additional textual content after final image with title "Suisengun kontairyaku kibun." Philadelphia University of Pennsylvania Rare Book & Manuscript Library LJS 454 6016920 http://hdl.library.upenn.edu/1017/d/medren/6016920 Scroll of diagrams and text concerning the construction and compartmentalization of European ships, referred to as battleships, all on the recto side. At the top of the scroll is a thin piece of wood and a tie that wraps around the scroll; a paper label in Japanese is on the verso of the beginning of the scroll. Sheets of a different kind of paper, of the same width but different length, are used for backing. Japanese Seiyō senpaku zukai translator Motoki, Shōei, 1767-1822

paper

 1 roll (34 sheets) : 37 x 894 cm Written in vertical columns of characters perpendicular to the length of the scroll. Written in Japanese script. 4 detailed full side diagrams of ships, 1 with a top pennant that unfolds above the upper edge of the scroll and 1 with a damaged foldout top pennant; 22 partial diagrams, including ship cross-sections and diagrams of astronomical and navigational equipment; many diagrams rubricated in red, some with syllables that are keyed to text describing the parts or areas of a ship.
